Date: Wed, 08 Sep 1999 19:05:15 -0400
From: Marjorie P. Pollack <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
[Connecticut and New Jersey respond to the situation in New York City. -
Mod.CHC
(a)
CONNECTICUT
<http://www.bostonherald.com/bostonherald/lonw/bugtest09081999.htm>
Source: Boston Herald AP wires, 8 Sep 1999

Health officials in Connecticut are testing mosquitoes for potentially
deadly St. Louis encephalitis after an outbreak in neighboring New York.
"Certainly, we are concerned," said Matthew Cartter, epidemiology program
coordinator for the state Department of Public Health. "This is the first
outbreak of the disease in the Northeast (in recent memory)." "If there is
evidence that the virus is in mosquitoes here, something will be started to
hinder them," said John Anderson, director of the Connecticut Agricultural
Experiment Station in New Haven.
Six mosquito traps were installed along the shoreline and inland sections
of Greenwich over the Labor Day weekend, and more will be set this week.
Traps were also set in Stamford. [n.b. - Greenwich and Stamford are two of
the wealthiest towns on the planet. - Mod CHC A total of 67 mosquitoes
were captured in Greenwich. Fourteen were _Culex_ mosquitoes, the breed
most commonly associated with the spread of SLE. It will be five or six
days before researchers know whether the mosquitoes are carrying St. Louis
encephalitis virus or Eastern equine encephalitis virus.
(b)
NEW JERSEY
Source: The Bergen County Record, 8 Sep 1999
<http://www.bergen.com/region/skeetjf199909083.htm>
[Nice story about mosquito surveillance being done in New Jersey.
Surveillance directors appear to be concerned and are increasing
surveillance frequency and intensity. Hospitals are increasing awareness
in looking for admissions with compatible illnesses. - Mod.CHC
